Why R?

Open source & FREE

  • Lots of online resources and tutorials that are also free
  • Large community of users
  • Endless applications with new tools always in development

Widely used in performing ecological analyses

  • Not uncommon to see R packages released alongside scientific articles describing new approaches or types of analysis
  • Also not uncommon for scientists to release their code with a publication

R basics

R packages

  • Packages are groups of tools, or functions, that contain code and data that allows us to more easily perform specific tasks.
  • For example, there are packages that allow for making flexible and customizeable graphs, and others that contain functions to perform a specific type of data analysis or data manipulation.
  • While ‘base R’ has a lot of built in functions, one of the strengths of R is that anyone can develop packages and share them with others.

R syntax: R objects

  • It is frequently useful to give datasets names and be able to reference them and work with them later. You can do this in R by assigning the data, or the result of a function, to an ‘object’.

  • Above, I am assigning the text string containing a file path to an object, so that I can reference it later.

R syntax: R objects

  • Now I want to read in a file, so instead of having to write out the whole file path again I can use the ‘path’ object.
myfile <- read.csv(paste0(path, "water_example.csv"))

  • In this case we use the function, ‘read.csv’ to read in the file, and the function ‘paste0’ to stitch together the text string that we have stored within the ‘path’ object and the name of the file.

  • now the data from the .csv file is stored in the object, ‘myfile’

Vectors & Data Frames

  • The most common way of storing data in R and the data structure weâll deal with most often for analysis is called a ‘data frame’
  • Data frames are made up of equal-length vectors
  • A ‘vector’ is a sequence of data elements of the same type

# Here is a vector:
vector <- c(0, 2, 4, 5, 7, 2)
vector
## [1] 0 2 4 5 7 2
# Here is a data.frame:
animal <- c("cat", "dog", "horse", "rabbit", "guinea pig", "chicken")
count <- c(7, 6, 5, 1, 2, 2)
df <- data.frame(animal, count)
df
##       animal count
## 1        cat     7
## 2        dog     6
## 3      horse     5
## 4     rabbit     1
## 5 guinea pig     2
## 6    chicken     2

Commenting

  • Commenting and annotating your code can be really useful and helps document your process
# comments and annotations are made by typing behind a '#' sign
print('you will never be sorry for commenting your code!') 
## [1] "you will never be sorry for commenting your code!"
# annotations are often placed before a section of code
print('but they can also be placed on the same line') # like this!
## [1] "but they can also be placed on the same line"
